This morning I woke up lusting for a Nescafe immersion coffee maker, but at £28.99 on eBay a lot of us have to just put up with poor instant coffee. And that’s why Nauru is beautiful: it means we can all be equally starved of coffee.

On Nauru, my first ever home, I grew up frying cassava, collecting rainwater to drink and adding bleach to buckets of it, and sometimes being scared of the waves on my front step. I am rude to my mother, who says I shouldn’t burn my food. I sense that she’s rediscovering her adolescence. One day, beset by an existential crisis about life graceless-here, our conversations are agreeable, cognate and comfortable. The schism subsides, and our childhoods are each the centre of the other’s universe again.

On Nauru, a virtual punchbag to a large egometer of an ageing society, young people like me look holistically now to achieve contemporary dreams of luxury and success that have become ossified rituals of the Fifties: the Ferraris and the iPhones and their visceral connection to the psychology of the consumer market. This year, the media might make a holiday to Nauru mandatory.
